T1  - The American Put Option Valued Analytically
AU  - GESKE, ROBERT
AU  - JOHNSON, H. E.
Y1  - 1984/12/01
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1984.tb04921.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1511
EP  - 1524
VL  - 39
IS  - 5
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1984.tb04921.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT An analytic solution to the American put problem is derived herein. The hedge ratio and other derivatives of the solution are presented. The formula derived implies an exact duplicating portfolio for the American put consisting of discount bonds and stock sold short. The formula is extended to consider put options on stocks paying cash dividends. A polynomial expression is developed for evaluating these formulae. Values and hedge ratios for puts on both dividend and nondividend paying stocks are calculated, tabulated, and compared with values derived by numerical integration and binomial approximation. As with European options, evaluating an analytic formula is more efficient than approximating the stock price process or the partial differential equation by binomial or finite difference methods. Finally, applications of this American put solution are discussed.
ER  - 

